News - Date: 02 September 2019 Written by: Tshifhiwa Mukwevho / Viewed: 112 A 22-year-old girl from Malamulele, Nkateko Khosa, might be the next Empress South Africa. She is currently a finalist, which means that she has clearly managed to pave a good path of her journey in the pageant so far. “Not only have I reached the semi-finals, but I am currently an ambassador for motofind.co.za,” she said. “And, as semi-finalists, we have been awarded the exciting ‘Warrior Princess’ title, which indicates Empress South Africa’s loving appreciation for our efforts and to encourage us to advance further into the finals.” Nkateko describes herself as an optimistic person who looks at things from a positive perspective. “God taught us how to trust in Him, and so I have,” she said. “That is exactly the best thing that I like about myself.” She stated that she had joined Empress South Africa because of her love for the community and the change she hopes to see. “I have always wanted to make a positive difference in my community, and I want to be a role model to the younger generation,” she said. Khosa gains influence from her surroundings, which is family. “The most influential person in my life is my aunt. She is whom I want to be like in the future,” she said. “I want to be kind, compassionate and a true example of a God-fearing woman.”  Nkateko Khosa is optimistic that she can win the Empress SA 2019 title.  Tshifhiwa Given Mukwevho was born in 1984 in Madombidzha village, not far from Louis Trichardt in the Limpopo Province. After submitting articles for roughly a year for Limpopo Mirror's youth supplement, Makoya, he started writing for the main newspaper. He is a prolific writer who published his first book, titled A Traumatic Revenge in 2011. It focusses on life on the street and how to survive amidst poverty. His second book titled The Violent Gestures of Life was published in 2014.  Email: givenmukwevho@yahoo.com